  "summary": "Bobby Hawkins receives a phone call from Frances \"Frankie\" Davenport, who requests a car at ten o'clock to take her to London. After the call, Frankie speaks with Roger Baskerville-French, explaining that she must travel to London due to her father's fuss. Roger asks to ride into town with her, but Frankie declines, noting she will have Higgins with her and needs to shop. As Bobby drives Frankie away, Roger holds her hand and expresses concern about her safety.\n\nOnce in the car, Frankie asks Bobby if Roger might be in love with her, but Bobby shifts the conversation to a significant discovery: he found the person from the photo found in the dead man's pocket at Dr. Nicholson's private nursing home. Frankie describes Dr. Nicholson as an imposing, suspicious man who probed her about her recent accident during dinner. She suggests that Nicholson may be the head of a drug cartel, using his rehabilitation center as a cover to legally obtain and distribute drugs.\n\nFrankie expresses a sudden intuition that Baskin-Fontaine might be innocent, despite Bobby's belief that the photo proves his guilt. They discuss the potential victim, Allen Castles, noting he was a nomadic individual who traveled to Stafford with a couple named Rivendale. They hypothesize that Castles may have been tracking Nicholson's gang or searching for the girl in the photo. Frankie reveals she used a fake letter from her father as an excuse to drive into town so she could speak with Bobby privately without being seen in Stavely's alleys.",
